Promising steps from state policymakers and practitioners have helped to create the conditions for the expansion of computer science education, yet student access remains limited and unevenly distributed. In California, the lack of publicly available data makes it difficult to examine changes in course availability and enrollment in response to a large investment in educator capacity building through the Educator Workforce Investment Grant in Computer Science (EWIG). Case studies of six California school districts help illuminate the evolution of computer science access over time and the contributing factors to emerging patterns. This poster shares findings about course availability and enrollment between 2018-19 and 2023-24 from the California Longitudinal Pupil Achievement Data System. Interviews with administrators and teachers in each district supplement quantitative findings by examining the nature of the computer science programming available, the motivation for the district's approach, and the dynamics that shape progress. Enrollment patterns varied by district, but each district featured declines in access and participation during the COVID-19 pandemic. Interviews revealed that although measuring standalone computer science courses is one indication of access, that approach insufficiently captures opportunities provided through the integration of computer science into other content areas and extracurricular activities. Interview and survey data consistently highlighted the value of EWIG-supported educator workshops in building knowledge, skills, and confidence, but also suggested that these opportunities alone may be insufficient to grow computer science education programs in districts and schools.